{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f0b8754-e449-4b35-9545-71c59986ef4c","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_5pVJtiCk6cXbpnWZHafKDu","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-064816e114e44546b2187b8e09259119"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-064816e114e44546b2187b8e09259119."}],"interactionId":"cf60ae16-587e-439c-9d05-49142675053c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields according to the .NET template engine spec.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required but strongly recommended for validation and editor support. Should be `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages that contain multiple templates or for template updates. Without it, updating the package may cause issues.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Used with `groupIdentity` to determine which template takes precedence when multiple versions are installed.\n\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Could be useful for better user experience.\n\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — That's fine since .NET 9 exists.\n\n6. **Missing `replaces` property on the Framework symbol** — The symbol is defined but won't actually substitute into project files without specifying what it replaces, so changing the framework selection won't update the `.csproj` target framework.\n\n7. **Missing `description`** — Strongly recommended for NuGet gallery display and discoverability in `dotnet new` search.\n\nI should also check if there are supporting files like a `.csproj` or `.nuspec` in the template directory that would be part of the template content.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"9C11:319933:1BE320C:1F608FE:6A07C004"},"id":"9727fd3b-e597-4c8f-bad2-7ad134bd4e84","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:53:35.566Z","parentId":"4c26f9c3-d296-4013-ba9